To achieve this, you can use Bootstrap for styling and jQuery for handling the click event. Here's an example code snippet:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Bootstrap Alert Example</title>
  <!-- Bootstrap CSS -->
  <link href="https://maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/4.5.2/css/bootstrap.min.css" rel="stylesheet">
  <!-- jQuery -->
  <script src="https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/3.5.1/jquery.min.js"></script>
  <style>
    /* Positioning the button */
    #alertButton {
      position: fixed;
      bottom: 20px;
      right: 20px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

<!-- Button to trigger the alert -->
<button id="alertButton" class="btn btn-primary">Show Alert</button>

<!-- Bootstrap Alert -->
<div id="myAlert" class="alert alert-success alert-dismissible fade" role="alert">
  This is a Bootstrap alert.
  <button type="button" class="close" data-dismiss="alert" aria-label="Close">
    <span aria-hidden="true">&times;</span>
  </button>
</div>

<script>
  // jQuery to handle button click
  $(document).ready(function(){
    $("#alertButton").click(function(){
      $("#myAlert").addClass("show"); // Adding 'show' class to display the alert
      $("#myAlert").alert(); // Initializing Bootstrap alert
    });
  });
</script>

<!-- Bootstrap JS -->
<script src="https://maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/4.5.2/js/bootstrap.min.js"></script>

</body>
</html>
```

In this code:

- The button is positioned at the bottom right using CSS.
- On button click, jQuery adds the "show" class to the alert, making it visible.
- Bootstrap's JavaScript is used to initialize the alert for dismissal functionality.
